Insurance today face challenges across the entire claims lifecycle, including inefficient FNOL intake, manual adjuster workflows, delayed investigations, vendor coordination complexities, and fraud detection across SIU operations.

Hexaware’s Agentic AI Claims Solution transforms the end-to-end claims journey through intelligent FNOL, AI-assisted adjuster workflows, proactive SIU investigation capabilities, document intelligence, vendor orchestration, and automated verification support, enabling insurers to deliver faster, more accurate, and customer-centric claim experiences while keeping humans at the center of every critical decision.

In the previous experience, we saw how the policyholder initiated a claim through the intelligent FNOL interface by simply describing the incident using voice or text. The AI automatically identified the loss type, extracted key details, validated intake information, generated a pre-filled FNOL report, and submitted the claim for further processing.

Once the FNOL is successfully submitted and the claim number is generated, the claim seamlessly moves into the adjuster workflow for assessment.

Now we will look at the Adjuster, followed by the SIU, or Special Investigation Unit.

As the claim is routed to the Adjuster Portal, the adjuster can view claim-related insights and click on Follow My Claims to see all the claims awaiting review. Opening a particular claim provides customer insights, and the adjuster can request additional information, schedule interviews, or respond to escalations.

The adjuster then opens the Loss Adjustments page, where detailed customer information, uploaded documents, and AI-powered investigation tools are available. A smart comparison section provides insights from similar claims in neighboring locations, showcasing comparable claims and settlement information.

The Verification Intelligence section validates customer-uploaded images against drone captures. Using AI-powered cross-referencing, the adjuster can verify the integrity of uploaded images before approving them or forwarding the claim to the SIU if required.

The adjuster can also review assigned vendors, access the Document Hub, where uploaded documents are automatically classified and summarized by AI, and approve or reject the submitted documents. Once document validation is complete, the adjuster concludes the intake validation, and the claim progresses to the loss investigation stage.

After completing the investigation, the adjuster can move the claim forward while requesting additional documentation from the policyholder whenever necessary.

Next, the adjuster initiates the AI-Assisted Loss Assessment. Running the AI analysis displays the loss calculation engine, including a summary of the estimated loss, applicable deductible, repair versus replacement recommendations for property claims, and repair versus total loss recommendations for motor claims.

The Repair vs. Replacement section provides a side-by-side comparison of both options, enabling the adjuster to make an informed decision.

Returning to the loss assessment, the adjuster can generate AI-assisted recommendations for claim approval or rejection. Based on fraud scoring, the AI may also recommend redirecting high-risk claims to the SIU. Although the platform supports Straight-Through Processing, or STP, human oversight remains central to every decision.

Even when AI recommends automated approval, the adjuster retains full authority to approve, reject, or escalate the claim for further investigation.

If suspicious indicators or inconsistencies are detected, the claim can be escalated to the Special Investigation Unit, or SIU.

Claims with fraud scores above the defined threshold are automatically flagged for SIU review, while adjusters can also manually escalate any claim whenever necessary.

Once forwarded, the claim appears in the SIU Portal, where investigators can review the complete claim timeline, request additional documentation, schedule interviews, and trigger external verification processes. The system also tracks SLA timelines to ensure investigations remain within compliance requirements.

After completing the investigation, the SIU can clear the claim and return it to the adjuster for further processing.

Throughout the process, claim statuses, investigation outcomes, and pending customer actions are continuously updated and reflected across the platform. Once the investigation is cleared, the adjuster reviews the latest claim activities and proceeds with claim approval through the loss assessment workflow.

Following approval, the system activates Smart Vendor Matching. Using AI-driven vendor intelligence scores, the platform automatically recommends the most suitable vendor for the repair work. The recommendation considers multiple factors, including skill specialization, licensing compliance, SLA performance, and other quality indicators.

The adjuster can either accept the AI-recommended vendor or manually select another vendor based on business requirements.

With Hexaware’s Agentic AI Claims Solution, this AI-orchestrated property and motor claims platform transforms the traditional claims lifecycle into an intelligent, customer-centric experience. The platform combines intelligent FNOL, AI-assisted assessment, proactive SIU investigation, centralized document intelligence, smart vendor orchestration, and automated verification capabilities into a unified ecosystem.

The result is faster settlements, reduced operational costs, lower claims leakage, improved adjuster productivity, and enhanced customer satisfaction, while ensuring that humans remain at the center of every critical decision, augmented by AI-driven intelligence and automation.
